channel.title: Hmm
channel.description:
I tried to change easyrsc.cfg to classic.cfg just so it looks nicer, and I changed the GUI to load "classic.cfg" instead of "easyrsc.cfg".
Everything compiled fine and I can click run server to bring up the GUI to start server but when I click start server it errors out. I tried changing back to easyrsc.cfg and it still errors out on me...
Did xEnt implement an anti leech so you can't change easyrsc's name? And if so does anyone know which files it corrupts to not start?

@RSCDevil

Don’t listen to them a lot of mopar gives awful advice usually Cleako is very knowledgeable so I would expect more from him then saying “get an ide”. Things like these are not solutions. His not asking for an IDE. Also it is more unnecessary work.

I’ll try to change the settings and see if I have any luck then update my post

Edit: I managed to do it:

Here is how:

Change name of the Easyrsc.cfg to Classic.cfg

Then go to GUI.Java

Find:(Should be line 119)

And change it to this(the name of your .cfg)

Next you can change these lines as well to make the panel look nicer.

Line:147

public GUI() { initComponents(); String configFile = "Easyrsc.cfg";//change here try { Config.initConfig(configFile); } catch (Exception e) { Logger.print(e, 1); } resetVars(); } static String[] args = null;

Line: 161

Line:1406

[code] label11.setText(“EasyRSC Created by xEnt”);//Change this here if you want
label11.setFont(new Font(“Tahoma”, Font.BOLD, 16));

					label12.setText("to Report Bugs or Suggestion, visit Moparscape in the EasyRSC Topic: ");//change this if you want
					label12.setFont(new Font("Tahoma", Font.PLAIN, 14));

					label13.setText("Based off the RSCD v25 source by Reines");//change this here if you want
					label13.setFont(new Font("Tahoma", Font.BOLD, 12));

					textField2.setText("http://www.moparisthebest.com/smf/index.php/topic,340170.0.html");//change this here[/code]

Line:1475

Compile and it should run. Remember to only change things in " " to avoid compile errors.

It should all compile and run fine and no I did not need an IDE to this.
